Chemical Geology

Volume 511, 20 April 2019, Pages 11-20

Grain scale processes recorded by oxygen isotopes in olivine-hosted melt inclusions from two MORB samples

Author links open overlay panel, , , , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.chemgeo.2019.02.025Get rights and content

Abstract

Although olivine-hosted melt inclusions from mid ocean ridge basalts (MORB) are commonly used as a proxy for mantle composition, these melt inclusions generally show larger elemental and isotopic compositional variation than their host lavas and the origin of these heterogeneities remains disputed. Here we present oxygen isotope data from melt inclusions hosted in olivine from two samples from the Mid-Atlantic ridge. Melt inclusions from different crystals within the same sample show >2.5â€° Î´18O variation within each sample, which is nearly eight times the analytical error of 0.3â€° (2 standard deviations) and five times the Î´18O range in unaltered MORB. Measured Î´18O in melt inclusions do not correlate with common magmatic tracers, and Î´18O measured in the host olivines suggest a maximum of 1â€° Î´18O source heterogeneity. Less than half of the melt inclusions from each sample are in equilibrium with their host crystals; the remaining melt inclusions have either lower or higher olivine-melt oxygen isotope partition coefficients compared to the theoretical equilibrium values. Here we discuss several potential processes that could contribute to these observations, but none satisfactorily explain the olivine-melt inclusion oxygen disequilibrium that we observe in these samples. Nevertheless, it seems clear that the variability of Î´18O in melt inclusion from two MORB samples do not record only common magmatic process(es), but rather a localized grain scale process. Any Î´18O variation in melt inclusions should thus be interpreted with caution.

1. Introduction

Olivine-hosted melt inclusions are often used to study the origin and evolution of mantle-derived magmas (for a review, see Kent, 2008; Schiano, 2003 and references therein). Melt inclusions are physically isolated from their host magma, which undergoes different processes during magmatic evolution after the entrapment of melt inclusions (for example, magma mixing, assimilation, degassing). An important observation is that larger elemental and isotopic compositional variations are generally observed in melt inclusions when compared to whole-rock or glass compositions. A widespread interpretation is that variations measured in melt inclusions reflect magmatic diversity that is not recorded in whole rock compositions due to obscuration during later processes (e.g., Kent, 2008). In some cases, variations could also be related to small-scale reactions in the melt in which the olivine is growing (Danyushevsky et al., 2004).

In mid-oceanic ridge basalts (MORB), most melt inclusions have trace-element compositions in the range of MORB lavas, but there are also some clear exceptions to this general observation (see Schiano, 2003 for a review). These â€˜anomalousâ€™ trace-element compositions have usually been interpreted to reflect near-fractional melting of a depleted mantle and/or spinel lherzolite, or of hydrothermally altered peridotite (e.g., Gurenko and Chaussidon, 1995; Nielsen et al., 2000; Sobolev and Shimizu, 1993). The anomalous trace-element compositions are not found in MORB rocks, as MORBs represent aggregates of different melt fractions (e.g., Jin et al., 1994; McKenzie, 1984; Sobolev and Shimizu, 1993). Melt reaction within the crust, i.e. within a crystal mush, may also explain the larger compositional variations observed in some MORB melt inclusions compared to lavas (e.g., Danyushevsky et al., 2004; Kamenetsky and Gurenko, 2007).

Major and trace element variability in melt inclusions from MORB samples are also sometimes observed within a single phenocryst (Shimizu, 1998), which indicates that melt inclusions are not necessarily in equilibrium with their hosts. Such small-scale diversity could be generated by trace element diffusion within the melt during melt inclusion formation by host dissolution-reprecipitation, or by boundary layer entrapment during fast, diffusion-controlled growth or melt transport (e.g., Baker, 2008; Cottrell et al., 2002; Faure and Schiano, 2005; Manzini et al., 2017; Van Orman et al., 2002). Other processes, such as diffusion of some elements (e.g., H, Fe) toward the host olivine or the host melt are responsible, in some cases, for elemental variation in melt inclusions (e.g., Danyushevsky et al., 2000a; Gaetani et al., 2012).

To date, no stable isotope data from melt inclusions within olivine from typical MORB samples have been published. Although Î´11B and Î´18O were reported in some olivine-hosted melt inclusions from Iceland, the petrogenetic history of these samples is fundamentally different from typical MORB settings (Gurenko and Chaussidon, 1997, Gurenko and Chaussidon, 2002; Hartley et al., 2013). In this study, we focus on Î´18O values from melt inclusions within MORB samples, as the systematics of this stable isotope system are well constrained. Based on a compilation of Î´18O data in Neogene volcanic rocks, Harmon and Hoefs (1995) concluded that bulk MORB rocks have Î´18O compositions of 5.7â€°â€¯Â±â€¯0.2â€°. Because the variation reported is similar to the typical analytical uncertainty reported in the literature for individual Î´18O measurements of silicate rocks at that time, the authors concluded that MORB have a uniform Î´18O signature. More recently, fresh MORB glasses from the Mid-Atlantic Ridge, Indian Ocean and east Pacific Ridge were analyzed by laser fluorination and show a narrow range of oxygen isotope ratios from 5.37â€¯Â±â€¯0.01 to 5.81â€¯Â±â€¯0.04â€° (1Ïƒ), with an average of +5.50â€° (Eiler et al., 2000). In addition, Î´18O is thought to not fractionate during melting (e.g., Eiler, 2001). As such, if melt inclusions are representative of the MORB source, they should show similar values within a relatively restricted range; however, as melt inclusions generally show larger chemical variations than those recorded by the bulk rock, Î´18O in melt inclusions from MORB samples might also display larger isotopic variabilities than MORB glasses. Constraining the variability of oxygen isotopes in melt inclusions from MORB samples is important, as Î´18O variations within these melt inclusions serve to assess the importance of fluid interaction, magma mixing and/or assimilation of oceanic crust (Gurenko and Chaussidon, 2002; Hartley et al., 2013). In this study we report Î´18O data from melt inclusions within two different MORB samples from the northern Mid-Atlantic Ridge. We observe a never before reported large range of Î´18O compositions within these melt inclusions, up to 2.5â€°, and discuss the reported data in term of magmatic processes, olivine dissolution-precipitation and diffusion.

2. Sample description and geological context

The studied olivine-hosted melt inclusions are from two dredged basalts from the North Atlantic ridge. Sample ARP73-10-03 is a picrite from the FAMOUS zone (36Â°8372â€²N, 33Â°2482â€²W) that contains a little >20% olivine phenocrysts (Fo87.2â€“91.3), rare clinopyroxene, and plagioclase xenocrysts. The crystals are surrounded by a hyalocrystalline groundmass composed of glass, plagioclase (An75â€“80) and olivine microlites (Fo86) (Laubier et al., 2007). Laubier et al. (2007) suggest that the variable major and trace element compositions of ARP73â€“10-03 melt inclusions reflect polybaric partial melting of a homogeneous mantle, followed by mixing in various proportions at either different degrees of melting or in different parts of the melting system.

CH77-DR6-203 is a dredged basalt from the 14Â° MAR triple junction (14.12Â°N, 45Â°W). This fresh sample is highly enriched in volatiles, with CO2 in vesicles and water in the glass, (popping rock; Javoy and Pineau, 1991) and shows a compositional anomaly with enriched (Nb/Zr)N, (Ta/Hf)N and (La/Sm)N compared to adjacent segments which may result from mantle heterogeneity (Bougault et al., 1988). The mantle heterogeneity hypothesis is also supported by Sr and Nd isotopes in MORB rocks from different segments of the triple junction (Dosso and Bougault, 1986). The melt inclusions studied here are hosted in 1â€“5â€¯mm, polyhedral olivines containing one or several melt inclusions. They are glassy, sub-spherical, and have a radius of 40â€“350â€¯Î¼m. They contain no daughter minerals. Rare shrinkage bubbles are present, but represent only a small fraction of the total volume.

3. Methods

3.1.1. Sample preparation

Polished olivines containing exposed melt inclusions were pressed into 1-inch indium mounts, along with the glass standards (BHVO-2G, BCR-2G and BIR-1G) and San Carlos olivine. Care was taken to mount them within 8â€¯mm of the center of the mount. A separate mount was made for each sample. SEM images were acquired at the University of Lausanne using a Tescan Mira LMU field-emission scanning electron microscope operated at 20â€¯kV and 0.2â€“0.4â€¯nA probe current to ensure that the melt inclusions were totally glassy. Melt inclusions with cracks or crystals were discarded. Topography of each mount was measured using a Brucker GTA-K white light interferometer.

3.1.2. Electron microprobe

Major element compositions and X-ray distribution maps of melt inclusions and olivines were acquired using a JEOL 8200 Superprobe electron microprobe analyzer. Analytical conditions for the quantitative measurement of olivine were 15â€¯kV at 20â€¯nA and a 5â€¯Î¼m beam diameter. Counting times were 30â€¯s for Si, Mg, Mn and Fe and 40â€¯s for Al, Ca, Ni and Cr. Analytical conditions for analyses of melt inclusions were 15â€¯kV, 10â€¯nA and a 10â€¯Î¼m beam diameter. Counting times were 30â€¯s for all elements except for K (20â€¯s) and Na (16â€¯s). A glass standard (KL2-G) was used for SiO2 and Al2O3. All other elements were calibrated on minerals. A grain of ML3B-G was used as an internal standard to check the calibration.

3.1.3. Secondary ion mass spectrometer

Oxygen isotope ratios, volatiles (H2O, CO2, Cl, F) and trace-element (Ti, V, Sr, Y, Nb, Ba, La, Ce, Nd, Sm, Eu, Yb) concentrations were determined using the CAMECA ims1280-HR at the SwissSIMS laboratory.

3.1.3.1. Oxygen isotopes

Analytical conditions were similar to those described by Seitz et al. (2017): Throughout 18O/16O measurements of melt inclusions and olivines, the sample was sputtered with a Cs+ primary beam of 2â€¯nA, which was raster over 15â€¯Î¼m. An electron gun was utilized in order to compensate for sample charging. Samples were pre-sputtered for 30â€¯s, followed by 80â€¯s of analysis (20â€¯cycles of 4â€¯s). Automatic centering of secondary ions on field and contrast apertures were performed before each analysis. Measurements of 16O and 18O were performed simultaneously via two Faraday cups, using 1010 and 1011 resistors, respectively. The intensity of 16O was typically ~ 2.2â€¯Ã—â€¯109 counts per second for glasses and ~1.7â€¯Ã—â€¯109 counts per second for olivine. Internal error (2 standard error), reflecting the counting statistics of one analysis, was usually better than 0.3â€° for melt inclusions and olivines.

For melt inclusions, instrumental mass fractionation (IMF) was corrected using a set of 9 international glass standards with compositions ranging from basaltic to rhyolitic (NKT-1G, GOR132-2G, BIR-2G, BHVO-2G, ML3B-2G, BCR-2G, StHs6/80G, UoE-Lipari, ATHO-G; Hartley et al., 2012; Jochum et al., 2006). The matrix effect was corrected using a linear regression of IMF with SiO2 (Fig. DR1-A). Two to three standards (BHVO, BIR and BCR), with compositions closely bracketing the melt inclusion compositions, were added on each mount to monitor and correct for potential instrumental drift. For olivines, IMF was corrected using an in-house San Carlos olivine standard (Fo 90.1), as well as three in-house olivine reference materials (Fo 99.6, Fo 91.9 and Fo 37.5; Fig. DR1DR1-B).

At the outset of each session, we performed at least eight measurements of a running standard (i.e., measured repeatedly during the session; BHVO for melt inclusions sessions and San Carlos for olivine sessions), in order to determine standard reproducibility (noted hereafter in 2 standard deviation, 2SD). The 2 SDs were better than 0.3â€° for melt inclusions sessions, and 0.4â€° for olivines sessions. To monitor the instrument stability, running standards were measured every 8 to 12 unknowns and gave a reproducibility of 0.3â€° 2SD, similar to the eight measurements at the outset of each session. Accuracy was checked using one of the two to three standards inserted in each mounts and was similar to reproducibility (0.3â€° 2SD and 0.4â€° 2SD for melt inclusions and olivines, respectively).

3.1.3.2. Trace elements

Phosphorous concentrations within melt inclusions were measured using the same analytical conditions described by Manzini et al. (2017): Trace-element compositions of melt inclusions and olivine were analyzed using a 5â€“6â€¯nA Oâ€“ primary ion beam, resulting in an analysis spot of about 20â€¯Î¼m. A mass resolution of 5000 was used. Samples were pre-sputtered for 90â€¯s, using a 25â€¯Î¼m raster. Trace elements were quantified by measuring the signal from the following isotopes: 48Ti, 51V, 88Sr, 89Y, 93Nb, 138Ba, 139La, 140Ce, 142Nd, 152Sm, 153Eu, 172Yb. These measurements were performed in mono-collection mode by peak switching throughout one analytical run on an electron multiplier (EM) collector. 40Ca was measured on a FC collector in the same analytical run as the other trace elements and was used as reference element. Using 40Ca instead of 30Si (or 28Si) during melt inclusion analyses allowed us to check for possible contamination by olivine throughout the analyses. A waiting time was used to obtain a steady state sputtering condition, and each analysis consisted of six cycles. Waiting and counting time, typical standard reproducibility and typical internal error are given in Table DR1. BHVO-2G was used as standard for melt inclusions, using the USGS certified values for the trace elements.

3.1.3.3. Volatile elements

A Cs+ primary ion beam with a current of 1.5â€¯nA was used to measure volatile elements (H2O, CO2, Cl, F, S); throughout these analyses an electron gun was used to compensate the charges and to avoid charging of the sample surface. The secondary beam was accelerated at 10â€¯kV, and the sample was pre-sputtered applying a 15â€¯Î¼m raster for 210â€¯s. Elements were measured in mono-collection mode, with a 10â€¯Î¼m raster during 12â€¯cycles. Total analysis time, including pre-sputtering, was approximately 14â€¯min. The field aperture was set to 3000â€¯Î¼m, entrance slit to 60â€¯Î¼m and exit slit to 240â€¯Î¼m. This configuration allowed a mass resolution of 5000, sufficient to fully discriminate the interferences. BHVO-2G, BCR-2G, BIR-1G, ALL, NS and ALV (Helo et al., 2011) were used as standards. BHVO-2G was then used as a running standard to check instrument stability. Background was determined by analysis of a synthetic anhydrous olivine. Additional information is given in Table DR1.

4. Results

A total of 34 melt inclusions within 30 olivines were measured from sample CH77-DR6â€“203, as were 17 melt inclusions within 13 olivines from sample ARP73â€“10-03. The results of these analyses are summarized in Table DR2. Oxygen isotope ratios in olivines are reported in Table DR3.

Analyzed olivines are characterized by a high forsterite content (Foâ€¯=â€¯Mg/Feâ€¯+â€¯Mg) ranging from 88.8 to 91.4 for ARP73-10-03 and from 84.0 to 90.9 for CH77-DR6â€“203. Major-element compositions of melt inclusions were corrected for the effect of post-entrapment crystallization (PEC) of olivine at the wall of melt inclusion, using the Petrolog software package (Danyushevsky and Plechov, 2011). Parameters used for Petrolog calculations are summarized in the footnote of Table DR2. Our calculated PEC indicates that between 5.9 and 18.1% of olivine crystallized after melt inclusion trapping. Major elements are less variable after PEC correction (e.g., SiO2 variation of 2.8â€¯wt% before and 1.6â€¯wt% after correction; Table DR2), and all major-element compositions mentioned hereafter are corrected for PEC. Melt inclusions from ARP73â€“10-03 have a narrow range of major-element compositions, with SiO2 ranging from 50.0â€“50.4â€¯wt%, MgO from 11.2â€“12.8â€¯wt% and K2O from 0.10â€“0.15â€¯wt%. CH77-DR6â€“203 shows a slightly larger compositional range in major elements, with SiO2 content from 49.2â€“50.8â€¯wt%, MgO from 7.8â€“10.0â€¯wt%, and K2O from 0.20â€“0.55â€¯wt% (Fig. 1A). Major-, volatile- (Cl, F, S) and trace-element concentrations measured in ARP73â€“10-03 fall within the same range as those reported by Laubier et al. (2012) for melt inclusions within the same sample and are consistent with glass N-MORB compositions (Jambon et al., 1995; Naumov et al., 2014; Wallace and Carmichael, 1992). Water and CO2 concentrations are also in the typical range of MORB glass values (Danyushevsky et al., 2000b; Magenheim et al., 1995; Wallace and Carmichael, 1992). The melt inclusions from CH77-DR6-203 are enriched in volatiles (to a lower extent for CO2) when compared with MORB glass values, and have trace-element compositions similar to typical E-MORB glasses (e.g., Fig. 1B modified from Gale et al., 2013).

Oxygen isotopes from melt inclusions show >2.3â€° variation within each sample (Î´18Oâ€¯=â€¯+5.0â€¯Â±â€¯0.17 to+7.2â€¯Â±â€¯0.16â€°, with an average of +6.2â€° for CH77-DR6â€“203; and Î´18Oâ€¯=â€¯+4.5â€¯Â±â€¯0.3 to +7.1â€¯Â±â€¯0.6â€°, averageâ€¯+â€¯5.7â€° for ARP73â€“10-03). These variations are about eight times larger than the analytical uncertainty (0.3â€°, 2SD) and about five times larger than the variations observed for bulk Î´18O of unaltered MORB glasses (<0.5â€°; Fig. 2). Before IMF correction, data show similar Î´18O variations (2.2â€°). This is explained by the relatively narrow range of SiO2 of the melt inclusions within a sample, which indicates that the applied IMFs are relatively similar (Â± 0.13â€°) for all melt inclusions from the same sample. ARP73â€“10-03 is the closest to MORB glass composition in term of major, trace elements and oxygen isotopes. Nevertheless, 8 melt inclusions out of 21 have â€˜anomalousâ€™ Î´18O composition (i.e., statistically â€“ 2 SD â€“ outside the range of MORB glass bulk values). Within a single olivine, Î´18O from different melt inclusions are statistically different in the ARP73â€“10-03 sample (3 pairs, variation up to 2.2â€°), whereas in the CH77-DR6â€“203 sample, melt inclusions hosted in a single olivine have values within analytical uncertainty Î´18O (3 pairs, variation <0.4â€°; Fig. 3). In both samples, olivines show smaller variability than their hosted melt inclusions: the ARP73-10-03 olivine have Î´18O values of +4.9 to +5.7â€° and olivines from CH77-DR6â€“203 have Î´18O ranging from +5.0 to +6.5â€° (Table DR3, Fig. 2).

5. Discussion

To date, no oxygen isotope data have been reported for olivine-hosted melt inclusions from MORB samples. Only two studies (Gurenko and Chaussidon, 2002; Hartley et al., 2013) reported Î´18O in olivine-hosted melt inclusions, and these data are from 7 samples taken from Iceland. These studies found Î´18O variation reaching a maximum of 1.2â€° (+4.0 to +5.2â€°, sample 14161G, nâ€¯=â€¯3 melt inclusions; Gurenko and Chaussidon, 2002) and 0.95â€° (+3.05 to +4.0â€°, sample N18, nâ€¯=â€¯9 melt inclusions; Hartley et al., 2013), respectively. These variations were interpreted to reflect either mixing of the ascending magma with melt lenses that had previously interacted with the low-Î´18O Icelandic crust (Hartley et al., 2013), or heterogeneity in the Icelandic mantle or mixing of two end-members (Gurenko and Chaussidon, 2002). Melt inclusions from the two MORB samples measured in our study both show >2.3â€° variation in Î´18O, a larger variation than that reported for olivine-hosted melt inclusions from Iceland. Hereafter, the Î´18O variability is discussed in term of analytical versus magmatic processes.

5.1. Analytical artefacts

Oxygen isotope analyses via SIMS are very sensitive to the sample geometry, i.e. the placement of the analyzed grains in the mount and the topography of the analyzed material (e.g., Kita et al., 2009). All grains and reference material have been placed within 8â€¯mm of the center of the mount, in order to avoid X-Y effects due to deformation of the electrostatic field close to the edge of the sample holder (Peres et al., 2013) (see methods section for more details). Reproducibility of the measurements of a homogeneous reference material for oxygen isotope is typically <0.3â€° (2 SD) when the surface relief is 1â€¯Î¼m, whereas it increases up to 3â€° (2SD) when topography is on the order of 10â€“40â€¯Î¼m (Kita et al., 2009). Our mounts show <4â€¯Î¼m topography both between the indium and grains, and between olivine and melt inclusions. Two different cases are presented in Fig. 4: First, Fig. 4-A shows olivine CH77-DR6â€“203_37 hosting 2 melt inclusions with similar Î´18O (within the 0.3â€° 2SD calculated for a session, +6.37â€¯Â±â€¯0.21â€° andâ€¯+â€¯5.97â€¯Â±â€¯0.16â€°) and a topography of 1â€¯Î¼m. Olivine ARP73â€“10-03_16, shown in Fig. 4-B, has Î´18O in melt inclusions which vary from +5.15â€¯Â±â€¯0.21â€° to +6.42â€¯Â±â€¯0.26â€°. This olivine has a topographical variation of up to 4â€¯Î¼m, with a difference in topography of 1.5â€¯Î¼m between melt inclusions A, C and D (maximum 1.3â€° difference in Î´18O), and 2.5â€¯Î¼m between melt inclusions A and B (similar Î´18O). Melt inclusions are <1â€¯Î¼m lower compared to the olivine, which should not affect the analyses: 17 analyses made following 2 profiles along perpendicular axes from wall to wall in melt inclusion A, and 7 in melt inclusion B yield a reproducibility better than 0.3â€° (2SD) (Table DR2). Also, multiple measurements (nâ€¯=â€¯75) located at the edge or in the center of the olivine grain ARP73â€“10-03_16, which shows the largest topographical variation, yield data clustering within 0.45â€° (2SD; Table DR3), comparable to the reproducibility obtained during the same session for San Carlos reference material that has negligible topography (0.40â€°, 2SD). Moreover, Î´18O from melt inclusions within ARP73â€“10-03_16 A and B were measured twice, in two different sessions and similar values were obtained. As the mount was placed in the sample holder with a different orientation, this confirms that measured Î´18O variation cannot be due to sample topography or orientation. Based on these observation, we find it highly unlikely that topography of the grains is responsible for the large variation of Î´18O in the melt inclusions analyzed in this study. As the calibration of the SIMS analyses reported here were made using several reference materials covering the range of melt inclusions major elements (Fig. DR2). Hence we conclude that the observed Î´18O variations are real in melt inclusions and do not represent analytical artefacts.

5.2. Effects of different magmatic processes

Partial melting causes large variations in the major- and trace- element concentrations of MORBs (e.g., Frey et al., 1993; Schilling et al., 1983; Zindler et al., 1979), but is not expected to largely fractionate oxygen isotopes. Indeed, Bindeman et al. (2012) estimate that extraction of 15% of the melt, assuming equilibrium is maintained throughout the melting, will change Î´18O by only 0.05â€°. Even high degrees of partial melting (up to 42%) of a mantle source will create <0.2â€° Î´18O variations (e.g. Eiler, 2001). Variation in the degree of partial melting will thus not be resolvable by SIMS, given the typical precision of ~0.3â€° 2SD. Hence, the lack of correlation between Î´18O and the abundance of incompatible elements such as [La/Sm]N for example (Fig. 1), which are sensitive to degree of melting, indicates that variable extents of partial melting cannot explain the large Î´18O scatter measured in this study. Interestingly, ARP73â€“10-03 has a composition similar to that of typical MORB glass (N-MORB) in terms of [La/Sm]N, K2O and volatile contents, and average Î´18O composition (e.g., Eiler et al., 2000; Gale et al., 2013), whereas CH77-DR6â€“203 has higher (La/Sm)N, volatiles, K2O contents, and Î´18O than that of N-MORB glass (Fig. 1). Differences in (La/Sm)N, volatiles and K2O contents between the two samples could reflect different degrees of melting, but the different average Î´18O rather suggests melting of an enriched mantle source for CH77-DR6â€“203. Despite the melting of different mantle sources for the two samples, resulting in different Î´18O for their respective melt inclusions, a similar variation of Î´18O (~2.5â€°) is observed in melt inclusions for both samples.

The lack of correlation between Î´18O of the melt inclusions and the forsterite content of their host olivines do not support large fractionation of oxygen isotopes during magmatic evolution of the studied samples (Fig. 5). This observation is consistent with an experimental study examining crystallization of a MORB melt dominated by olivine and plagioclase fractionation (Tormey et al., 1987), which shows that the oxygen isotopic composition of the melt should not vary by >0.1â€° for a MgO content between 3 and 8â€¯wt% (Eiler, 2001). Recently, Bucholz et al. (2017) modeled change in Î´18O in tholeiite during fractional crystallization and also found minor change in Î´18O (up to 0.35â€° for composition comparable to ARP73â€“10-03 and CH77â€“203-DR3 melt inclusions).

Considering the low volatile concentrations in MORB lavas, the effect of magma degassing on oxygen isotopes should be negligible. In fact, the total devolatilization of MORB magmas will change the Î´18O by <0.1â€° (Eiler, 2001). Similarly, oxygen fugacity changes in the magmatic system should not create any oxygen isotope ratio variations as the fractionation of oxygen isotopes in the melt is not controlled by fO2 (Lester et al., 2013).

Assimilation of altered oceanic (AOC) crust with variable Î´18O (1â€“6â€° for lower AOC and 7â€“15â€° for upper AOC; e.g. Alt, 2003; Alt and Bach, 2006) may also affect the Î´18O variability observed in melts (e.g., Genske et al., 2013). The assimilation process can be modeled by simple mixing, because MORB melts and AOC have very similar oxygen concentrations. If we consider a typical mantle composition of Î´18Oâ€¯=â€¯5.5â€° (Eiler, 2001; Mattey et al., 1994) and mix it with an altered upper oceanic crust with Î´18Oâ€¯=â€¯15â€° (e.g., Alt, 2003), a minimum of 17% assimilation of upper AOC is required to explain the highest Î´18O measured in melt inclusions (7.1â€°) from ARP73â€“10-03. This amount of upper AOC assimilation (>17%) would, for example, result in Ba content of >62â€¯ppm, assuming an average Ba content of the upper AOC of 300â€¯ppm (e.g., Kelley et al., 2003) and 13.9â€¯ppm for uncontaminated MORB (Hofmann, 1988). As melt inclusions from ARP73â€“10-03 (N-MORB sample), have Ba contents typical of N-MORB (around 20â€¯ppm; maximum 34â€¯ppm Ba), we find that assimilation of upper crustal material is not likely to be responsible for the high Î´18O values measured in these melt inclusions. Similarly, a minimum of 22% assimilation of the upper AOC is required to obtain the lowest Î´18O (4.5â€°) of the melt inclusions, assuming an extreme lower AOC composition of Î´18Oâ€¯=â€¯1â€° (as in hydrothermal amphibolite veins; e.g., Alt and Bach, 2006). Assimilation of serpentinites that have Î´18O values of 2.0 to 6.7â€°, with most of the values <5â€° (Barnes et al., 2014; Boschi et al., 2008) would require a larger amount of assimilation compared to AOC, and could not account for the Î´18O up to 7.1â€° or down to 4.5â€°.

The absence of correlation between elements that are similarly incompatible in the dissolution reactions of pyroxene, plagioclase and spinel (e.g., S and Ce; Danyushevsky et al., 2004) suggests that local grain-scale dissolution-reaction mixing processes (Danyushevsky et al., 2004) is an unlikely process to explain the Î´18O variations in melt inclusions. In fact, open system local dissolution of minerals formed in equilibrium with a basaltic melt will not change the Î´18O composition of the ascending basaltic melt.

The Î´18O variability of 1.1 and 1.4â€° in the olivine crystals (Î´18O(Ol)) from ARP73â€“10-03 and CH77-DR6â€“203 (Table DR3), respectively, is an indicator that these olivine crystals record crystallization in a heterogeneous environment, or record a heterogeneous crystallization history. Considering the typical reproducibility of olivine measurements of 0.4â€°, these variations are not likely to reflect analytical artefacts and should therefore represent real heterogeneities. In fact, individual crystals are homogeneous within measurement uncertainty of ca. 0.4â€°, while different crystals from the same sample are more variable. In terms of major elements, each crystal is homogeneous (with the exception of P heterogeneities in some olivines; Manzini et al., 2017), but all olivines have different Fo contents (Table DR3). Within each sample, no clear trend is observed between Fo content and average Î´18O(Ol) (Fig. 5). At a given Fo content, Î´18O(Ol) varies up to 0.9â€°. This observation suggests that these olivine crystals from both samples grew in slightly heterogeneous environments (~0.9â€“1â€° variation).

5.3. Olivine-melt inclusion isotopic disequilibrium

Equilibrium fractionation between olivine and melt (Î”18Ool-melt) at 1250â€¯Â°C is âˆ’0.6â€°, based on Matthews et al. (1998), which is equivalent to twice the uncertainty of the measured compositions. As mentioned above, Î”18O variability in the studied melt inclusions is larger than the heterogeneity of their host olivines. Only 42 and 46% of melt inclusions from ARP_73â€“10-03 and CH77â€“203-DR6 are in equilibrium with their host (Fig. 3). The remaining melt inclusions have either lower or higher Î”18Ool-melt compared to the theoretical equilibrium value at 1250â€¯Â°C. While the proportion of melt inclusions in equilibrium with their host olivine is similar for both samples, the proportion of melt inclusions with higher versus lower Î”18Ool-melt is different for each sample. In detail, within an olivine containing several exposed melt inclusions, Î”18Ool-melt can vary significantly. No correlation is observed between olivine-melt isotopic disequilibrium and Fo content of the host olivine, which indicates that disequilibrium conditions could have prevailed at any time during the samples' magmatic history. An important observation is that melt inclusions in equilibrium with their host olivines do not show significant Î´18O variation (5.7â€¯Â±â€¯0.3â€° for ARP73â€“10-03 and 6.3â€¯Â±â€¯0.5â€° for CH77â€“203-DR6). Assuming equilibrium between olivine and melt, variations in temperature throughout crystal growth could affect Î”18Ool-melt. However, the large variation of Î”18Ool-melt would require a large and unrealistic temperature range, from 700â€¯Â°C for the lowest Î”18Ool-melt to >2500â€¯Â°C for the positive Î”18Ool-melt.

We propose that the measured Î”18Ool-melt variations instead indicate disequilibrium. Lower or higher Î”18Ool-melt compared to theoretical equilibrium require either a process able to shift the equilibrium toward both higher and lower values, or a combination of different processes. Oxygen diffusion along the moving interface between melt and crystal during crystal growth or after melt inclusion entrapment is a process capable of generating isotopic disequilibrium between melt inclusions and their host olivine. Rapid crystal growth can lead to a local disequilibrium in the growth media, creating boundary layers in which elements with the lowest diffusivity in the melt and/or lowest partition coefficients (e.g., S, Cl, P, Al) will concentrate. It has been demonstrated that this process can create melt inclusion compositions with different major elements (Faure and Schiano, 2005; Watson and MÃ¼ller, 2009), volatiles (S, Cl) and/or P content (Baker, 2008) compared to the bulk melt composition. Oxygen is also a slow diffusing element in relatively dry melts, with 16O diffusing faster than 18O (e.g., Lesher, 2010); therefore, such a boundary layer should have a higher Î´18O composition than the melt in which the crystal in growing. Melt inclusions from ARP-73-10-03 have major, trace and volatile elements compositions similar to MORB, with no enrichment in Al, S, Cl or Ca; however, some melt inclusions within this sample do have higher P contents due to olivine dissolution near P-rich (fast growing) domains (Manzini et al., 2017). No significant difference in Î´18O(Ol) between P-rich and P-poor domains within each olivine are observed (Fig. DR2). Moreover, Î´18O(Ol) compositions of the recrystallized olivine (P-depleted halo) are similar to those of the primary olivine (Fig. 6A). Fig. 6B shows the Î´18O of melt inclusions from both samples, as a function of their location (in primary olivine, or in recrystallized domains), based on phosphorus maps of the host olivines. No systematic shift in Î´18O as a function of the olivine domain in which the melt inclusion is trapped can be resolved. Also, isotopic disequilibrium can be found in melt inclusions trapped in olivine with or without P zoning (Table DR2), suggesting that the MI-Olivine Î´18O disequilibrium and large Î´18O variations in melt inclusions are not related to initial rapid crystal growth creating P-rich domains, nor to the dissolution of P-rich olivine domains.

As argued above, olivine-hosted melt inclusions within the samples studied here suffered from PEC of olivine. Manzini et al. (2017) have shown that this thin (< 1â€¯Î¼m) layer crystallizes a few hours before eruption. This fast crystallization results in a strong P enrichment of the late-crystallized olivine. Post-entrapment crystallization could thus generate a thin boundary layer with a distinct (high) Î´18O(Ol) composition and lower the initial Î´18O of the melt inclusions. Given the small volume of the PEC (1â€¯Î¼m layer compared to melt inclusion diameters of >50â€¯Î¼m), it should not largely influence the melt inclusion composition. This assumption is verified by the absence of a correlation between amount of PEC or P with Î´18O of the melt inclusions or Î”18O ol-melt.

Diffusion of O in and out of the melt inclusions could in theory produce higher or lower Î”18Ool-melt. Oxygen can diffuse as mono or multi-species. Indeed, O is present in CO2 and H2O molecules. It is known that water can diffuse in or out of melt inclusions (e.g., Chen et al., 2013; Gaetani et al., 2012; Portnyagin et al., 2008), but mostly in the form of H+. Given the low water content involved in MORB systems, this should not produce large Î´18O variations in melt inclusions (Zhang and Ni, 2010). It is possible that CO2 could largely degas in melt inclusion shrinkage bubbles (e.g., Moore et al., 2015); migration of CO2 in the bubble may fractionate Î´18O, but as 16O is diffusing faster this could only generate higher Î´18O. Melt inclusions with the lowest Î”18Ool-melt do not necessarily contain shrinkage bubbles, which indicates that fractionation of O isotopes is not related to shrinkage bubble formation.

Diffusion of O after melt inclusion entrapment would imply that melt inclusions were initially not in equilibrium with their host at the time of entrapment and thus cannot explain the origin of the large variation of Î´18O in the studied melt inclusions. If O isotopic diffusion occurred after melt inclusion entrapment, it should be limited based on the following observations: First, based on P profiles made from melt inclusions in olivines, melt inclusions were trapped for a few hours to a few days before quenching (Manzini et al., 2017). Using the diffusion data of Dohmen et al. (2002) (this dataset yields a diffusion coefficient of ~9.3â€¯Ã—â€¯1012 in olivine at 1250â€¯Â°C), this amount of time would result in a small amount of O diffusing from melt inclusion to olivine over a profile no longer than 10â€¯Î¼m, which is not resolvable using the techniques employed in this study. This is confirmed by Î´18O profiles obtained from three different olivines, in which melt inclusions are either in disequilibrium (Figs. 7A and DR2) or equilibrium (Fig. 7B), starting at ~15â€“30â€¯Î¼m from the inclusion wall, do not show any significant increase or decrease of Î´18O values toward the MI. Second, Î´18O profiles measured within a single melt inclusion, from olivine wall to MI center, give similar values (Fig. 8). Lastly, there is no correlation between the melt inclusion size and the Î´18O value of the melt inclusion.

In theory, oxygen diffusion could occur in response to a thermal gradient (Soret diffusion). Indeed, Kyser et al. (1998) and Bindeman et al. (2013) reported significant isotopic fractionation of oxygen isotopes (up to 5.0â€°) in anhydrous basaltic melt due to thermal diffusion, with migration of 18O toward the colder regions. However, such a process has never convincingly been demonstrated in natural samples. Kyser et al. (1998) pointed out that, even if thermally induced diffusion can lead to large Î´18O fractionation, the rapid decay of thermal gradient (< 10â€¯days for 100Â° gradient at 1â€¯cm from contact) makes it an unlikely process to happen in natural samples. Given the short timescale associated with the olivine residence time and melt inclusion formation in our samples (Manzini et al., 2017), a locally large thermal gradient (>250â€¯Â°C) between migrating magma and conduit walls might be sustained before melt inclusion trapping. Assuming such a scenario, melt inclusions with Î´18O lower might form in olivine located in the center of a conduit, whereas melt inclusions with higher Î´18O would form close to the walls of the conduit; however, olivine crystallizing around the melt inclusions should also have variable Î´18O, which is not observed. This observation indicates that O diffusion in response to a thermal gradient is not responsible for the Î´18O variation in melt inclusions.

6. Concluding remarks

The large variations (up to 2.5â€°) observed in oxygen isotope ratios within melt inclusions from 2 different Atlantic MORB samples (N-MORB and E-MORB) are not correlated with major, trace or volatile elements. Oxygen isotope compositions of host olivines suggest a small (<1â€°) source heterogeneity for each sample. Less than half of the melt inclusions from each sample are in isotopic equilibrium with their host olivines. The remaining melt inclusions have either lower or higher isotopic fractionation compare to theoretical equilibrium values. Boundary layer entrapment will only shift Î´18O toward higher values, and the present dataset does not support this hypothesis. Fractionation diffusion of O during CO2 migration into the shrinkage bubble will shift Î´18O toward lower values, but no evidence of this process has been found. Another process capable of generating Î´18O fractionation both higher and lower than equilibrium values is O diffusion in due to the presence of a thermal gradient before melt inclusion entrapment (i.e. Soret diffusion). Although this process could explain the large Î´18O variation measured, it would imply that a large, unrealistic, thermal gradient (> 250â€¯Â°C) is sustained during the formation of melt inclusions. In addition, the olivine directly surrounding the melt inclusion should also have a different Î´18O in this scenario, which we do not observe.

Despite the marked disequilibrium in a majority of melt inclusions, our data do not show any significant O diffusion in or out the melt inclusions. This is due to the short residence time at high temperature after melt inclusion entrapment and the relatively large spatial resolution of the SIMS (10â€“15â€¯Î¼m). The exact process responsible for the melt inclusion-host Î´18O disequilibrium is thus not yet fully understood. Nonetheless, we argue that this dataset clearly shows that melt inclusions do not necessarily record the Î´18O composition of the magma in which their host grew. Caution should thus be taken before interpreting Î´18O variation as source process, especially when not related to any other tracer of common magmatic processes.

  • Melt inclusion formation during olivine recrystallization: Evidence from stable isotopes

    2022, Earth and Planetary Science Letters
    Citation Excerpt :

    The proportion of remobilized and partly recrystallized crystals could provide valuable information about the plumbing system of a volcano: a high proportion of remobilized olivine suggests a high proportion of crystals in the last melt pocket, or that the ascending melt has scavenged crystals from different melt pockets as it ascended. Olivine partial dissolution due to temperature increase and/or decompression, followed by infilling with a melt not necessarily in elemental and isotopic equilibrium with the initial olivine, explains the different major and trace element compositions of OHMIs trapped in a single crystal (e.g., olivines SVN181 from St. Vincent, Ao3-1, Ao15-10 olivines from Aoba in this study, or, for example ARP73-10-03_16, CH77-DR6-203_45 and CH77-DR6-203_55 from Mid-Atlantic Ridge, in Manzini et al., 2019). Such episodes of remobilization or mixing might not always be evident based solely on the major element composition of the olivine, due to fast Fe-Mg diffusion (e.g., Jurewicz and Watson, 1988; Gaetani and Watson, 2002).

    Melt inclusions are often used to infer melting processes or to determine source magmas that are usually overprinted in bulk rocks due to late stage mixing or near surface contamination. Here we present the first investigation of oxygen (O) isotope equilibrium between melt inclusions and their host olivines from arc samples. Olivines in all but one sample record either magma mixing or fractional crystallization. All six melt inclusions from Vulcano, 83% of seven from Sukumoyama, 44% of 21 from St Vincent, 37% of four from Iwate, and 21% of 13 from Aoba are not in isotopic equilibrium with their olivine host, despite the other major elements being in apparent equilibrium. A detailed study of some of the olivines shows that only a small volume around the melt inclusions is in equilibrium with its host. This strongly suggests that in these olivines melt inclusions are trapped in partly recrystallized olivines, highlighting the importance of magma mixing and crystal recycling in the magmatic plumbing system of these volcanoes. Oxygen isotope fractionation between melt inclusions and their host olivines, as well as phosphorus-O systematics, could be used to better understand the formation of melt inclusions and crystal history. It could also provide valuable information to help characterize the magmatic plumbing system that the inclusions and their olivine hosts formed in (e.g., crystal rich-mush versus crystal poor melt lenses).
